Serializes a `steno::bin::viz_data::tree::Tree` into the exact JSON shape `viz/index.html` expects to render: `{"categories": [...], "nodes": {...}}`. Hand-rolled string building rather than `serde` — the crate has a zero-runtime-deps invariant — reusing only `steno::json_string` for escaping.

The wire shape is entirely load-bearing and duplicated nowhere else in Rust: `viz/index.html` (not in this crate) parses these exact keys — `label`, `roots`, `terminal`, `multiLine`, `oneLiner`, `children`, `axis`, `kind`, `options`, `description`, `oneLinerRoot`, and per-choice `label`/`key`. Renaming a field or changing `null`-vs-omitted handling here silently breaks the viewer with no compile-time signal. Node key casing (camelCase) intentionally diverges from Rust field naming (`multi_line` → `"multiLine"`, etc.) to match JS conventions — this is deliberate, not an oversight.

`to_json(tree: &Tree) -> String` is the sole public entry point and builds the whole document via string concatenation. Node ordering is not alphabetical or `HashMap` order — `write_nodes` iterates `tree.node_order` (a separate `Vec<String>` on `Tree` tracking first-seen order) and looks up each key in the `nodes: HashMap<String, Node>`, silently skipping any key in `node_order` missing from `nodes` (no error, no panic). Optional fields (`multi_line`, `one_liner`, `axis`, `description`, `one_liner_root`) serialize to JSON `null` when `None`, never omitted. Output is not minified — commas and newlines are inserted manually per element with careful `i + 1 < len` boundary checks to avoid trailing commas; get one of those wrong and you emit invalid JSON with no test catching it unless the viz build/tests actually parse the output.